tre, authentic historical understanding demanded a much more personal and committed narrative, a kind of interpretive diary of moral choices and risks compelled by critical necessity and an exacting reality. Sartre's history, a rational history of individual lives and their intrinsic social worlds, was in essence immersed in biography. In Volume One of this authoritative two-volume work, Thomas R. Flynn conducts a pivotal and comprehensive reconstruction of Sartrean historical theory, and provocatively anticipates the Foucauldian counterpoint to come in Volume Two.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGeography. 0aHistory. 0aSartre, Jean Paul. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aphilosophy, history, sartre, foucault, poststructuralism, existentialism, choice, realism, fact, value, truth, objectivity, subjectivity, nonfiction, historiography, historian, structure, biography, constructivism, lacan, althusser, transformation, displacement, narrative, morality, risk, nietszche, change, discourse, marxism, capitalism, production, self.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226254692423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226254692/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles